    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i tried a log transform but the residuals are still looking pretty wonky in some parts of the distribution. if i go with robust regression, like RANSAC or something, how much does that actually change the coefficients compared to the standard OLS? also, are there any other ways to handle the non-normality if transformations don't work?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Robust regression methods like RANSAC are designed to provide more stable coefficient estimates by downweighting the influence of outliers, meaning the coefficients will likely differ from OLS, especially if the outliers are substantial. If transformations fail, a more advanced approach is to switch to non-parametric methods or use Generalized Linear Models (GLMs). GLMs allow you to specify different error distributions (like Poisson or Gamma) that better match the nature of your dependent variable beyond the normal distribution assumption.",
      "source": "target",
