    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. what about the heteroscedasticity though? i'm seeing the variance increase as the predicted values go up. is it better to just use weighted least squares or should i be looking at something like a Box-Cox transformation to try and stabilize that variance?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Since you've identified heteroscedasticity—where the variance increases with predicted values—Weighted Least Squares (WLS) is a very direct and effective solution. WLS accounts for the non-constant variance by assigning lower weights to the observations with higher variance, effectively correcting the standard errors. However, if the pattern of increasing variance is systematic, applying a Box-Cox transformation to your dependent variable might also help stabilize the variance across the range of predictions.",
      "source": "target",
